04389nam a22007815i 9780231521666DE-B159720220302035458.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220302t20092009nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a2009014162  a(OCoLC)1013956716  a97802315216667 a10.7312/mala145242doi  a(DE-B1597)459088  a(OCoLC)979745616  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY00aB809.7b.M2313 2010 4aB809.7bM353 2012 7aPHI0270002bisacsh04a1942231 aMalabou, Catherine, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aPlasticity at the Dusk of Writing :bDialectic, Destruction, Deconstruction /cCatherine Malabou. 1aNew York, NY : bColumbia University Press, c[2009] 4c©2009  a1 online resource (136 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aInsurrections: Critical Studies in Religion, Politics, and Culture00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tForeword -- tTranslator’S Introduction -- tVariations I -- tAfterword of the impossibility of fleeing – plasticity -- tNotes0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aA former student and collaborator of Jacques Derrida, Catherine Malabou has generated worldwide acclaim for her progressive rethinking of postmodern, Derridean critique. Building on her notion of plasticity, a term she originally borrowed from Hegel's Phenomenology of Spirit and adapted to a reading of Hegel's own work, Malabou transforms our understanding of the political and the religious, revealing the malleable nature of these concepts and their openness to positive reinvention. In French to describe something as plastic is to recognize both its flexibility and its explosiveness-its capacity not only to receive and give form but to annihilate it as well. After defining plasticity in terms of its active embodiments, Malabou applies the notion to the work of Hegel, Heidegger, Levinas, Levi-Strauss, Freud, and Derrida, recasting their writing as a process of change (rather than mediation) between dialectic and deconstruction. Malabou contrasts plasticity against the graphic element of Derrida's work and the notion of trace in Derrida and Levinas, arguing that plasticity refers to sculptural forms that accommodate or express a trace. She then expands this analysis to the realms of politics and religion, claiming, against Derrida, that "the event" of justice and democracy is not fixed but susceptible to human action.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aDerrida, Jacques. 0aDialectic. 0aPhilosophy, Frenchy20th century. 0aPhilosophy. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Movements / Deconstruction.2bisacsh1 aCrockett, Clayton, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCrockett, Clayton.1 aShread, Carolyn, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aShread, Carolyn.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertColumbia University Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311044247240uhttps://doi.org/10.7312/mala1452440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780231521666423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780231521666/original  a978-3-11-044247-2  Columbia University Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK